{% extends "demo.html.j2" %}

{% set split = card_data.split %}
{% set sizer = split[0] %}
{% set picker = split[1] %}
{% set decay = card_data.decay %}
{% set gate = card_data.powergate %}

{% block head_extra %}
<link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ asset_base | default('') }}assets/pages/s3.css">
{% endblock %}

{% macro slope_stat(m) %}
<div class="interval-stat" data-domain="slope"
     data-lo="{{ m.slope.ci_low }}" data-point="{{ m.slope.point }}" data-hi="{{ m.slope.ci_high }}">
  <span class="interval-stat__label">Fama&ndash;MacBeth sizing slope</span>
  <span class="interval-stat__value">{{ "%+.4f"|format(m.slope.point) }}</span>
  <div class="interval-stat__rail"><div class="interval-stat__band"></div>
    <div class="interval-stat__point"></div></div>
  <span class="interval-stat__range">t = {{ "%+.2f"|format(m.slope.tstat) }} &middot;
    month-cluster 95% [{{ "%+.4f"|format(m.slope.ci_low) }}, {{ "%+.4f"|format(m.slope.ci_high) }}]</span>
</div>
{% endmacro %}

{% block demo_content %}
<section class="s3-split">
  {% for m in [sizer, picker] %}
  <article class="s3-manager s3-manager--{{ m.role }}"
           data-scatter="{{ m.sizing_scatter | tojson | forceescape }}">
    <header class="s3-manager__head">
      <h3>{{ m.name }}</h3>
      <span class="verdict-chip" data-verdict="{{ 'robust' if m.slope.detected else 'noise' }}">
        {{ "sizing contribution detected" if m.slope.detected else "sizing contribution unresolved" }}</span>
    </header>
    <p class="s3-manager__alpha">Realized synthetic-path idiosyncratic alpha
      <strong>{{ "%+.1f"|format(m.alpha_annual * 100) }}%/yr</strong>, information ratio (IR)
      {{ "%.2f"|format(m.ir) }}
      <span class="verdict-chip" data-verdict="neutral">descriptive path output</span></p>
    {{ slope_stat(m) }}
    <svg class="s3-scatter" viewBox="0 0 100 60" preserveAspectRatio="none" role="img"
         aria-label="Per-position active contribution against position size"></svg>
  </article>
  {% endfor %}
</section>

<section class="s3-exhibit-shows">
  <h2>What this exhibit shows</h2>
  <p><strong>What you are looking at:</strong> two synthetic managers holding the
  <em>identical</em> book of picks &mdash; same names, same entry and exit dates, same holding
  ages &mdash; who differ in exactly one thing: how they size. Their returns look markedly
  different even though their picks are the same.</p>
  <p><strong>How to read it:</strong> the sizing slope asks whether bigger synthetic positions
  earned more on this controlled path. A month-cluster interval that clears zero identifies a
  sizing contribution in this construction; one that straddles zero leaves it unresolved.
  Realized path summaries below are descriptive, while inferential slopes carry intervals and
  the low-trade case refuses. This controlled synthetic example isolates sizing, but it does not
  establish manager intent, live prevalence, external calibration, or a live conviction premium.
  Cluster axis: {{ card_data.meta.cluster_axes | join('×') }} (months);
  <a href="{{ asset_base | default('') }}specs/s3.html">Technical method and provenance</a>
  derives the date&times;name live extension.</p>
</section>

<section class="s3-verdict">
  <p>The two managers hold identical synthetic picks, so the realized
  <strong>{{ "%+.1f"|format(card_data.sizing_value.gap_annual * 100) }}%/yr</strong>
  gap is this path's <strong>realized synthetic-path sizing contribution</strong>
  <span class="verdict-chip" data-verdict="neutral">descriptive subtraction</span>.
  The verdict for {{ picker.name }} is not &ldquo;redeem&rdquo;: this controlled comparison
  isolates a sizing mechanism; this is a sizing conversation, not evidence of manager intent.
  {{ picker.name }}'s own small non-zero slope is a long-vs-short position-size step &mdash;
  equal-weight within each side, but the sides differ &mdash; not conviction, so its statistical
  insignificance is the honest verdict.</p>
  <p class="s3-reference-effect">At the calibration study's reference effect (realized
  information ratio &approx; 0.65), the sizing
  slope <strong>never clears 80%</strong> power within 120 months, so this strong-effect exhibit does
  not contradict the broader calibration result.</p>
</section>

<section class="s3-decay">
  <h2>Alpha-decay curve</h2>
  <p>Pooled across {{ card_data.meta.decay_max_age }}-age validation replications the fitted
  half-life lands at <strong>{{ "%.2f"|format(decay.half_life_pooled) }} months</strong> against a
  dialled {{ "%.1f"|format(decay.dial_truth) }}. The <strong>entry</strong> month is shown separately
  (ages-0&ndash;12 fit {{ "%.2f"|format(decay.half_life_ages_0_12) }}) because it carries the extra
  selection premium. For a <em>single</em> manager the half-life band is honestly wide &mdash;
  roughly {{ "%.0f"|format(decay.single_manager_ci.lo) }} to {{ "%.0f"|format(decay.single_manager_ci.hi) }}
  months &mdash; and the page shows that width, not a false-precise point.</p>
  <svg class="s3-decay-svg" data-curve="{{ decay.curve | tojson | forceescape }}"
       viewBox="0 0 100 50" preserveAspectRatio="none" role="img"
       aria-label="Directional idiosyncratic return by holding age"></svg>
</section>

<section class="s3-holding">
  <h2>Holding-period decomposition</h2>
  <div class="s3-holding-bar"
       data-shares="{{ card_data.holding.shares | tojson | forceescape }}"
       data-order="{{ card_data.meta.holding_buckets | tojson | forceescape }}"></div>
  <ul class="s3-holding-legend">
    {% for label in card_data.meta.holding_buckets %}
    <li>{{ label }}: <strong>{{ "%.0f"|format(card_data.holding.shares[label] * 100) }}%</strong></li>
    {% endfor %}
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="s3-powergate">
  <div class="power-gate">
    <span class="power-gate__title">Not enough independent trades</span>
    <p class="power-gate__reason">
      Only {{ gate.independent_trades }} of
      {% if gate.hit_rate_threshold %}~{{ gate.hit_rate_threshold }}{% else %}the required{% endif %}
      independent trades are available, so the hit-rate result is withheld. Sizing skill is
      <strong>indistinguishable from luck</strong> for this book. The ~780 threshold applies to
      the hit-rate check; the sizing check uses the strong effect demonstrated above.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
{% endblock %}

{% block methodology %}
<p>The sizing slope is a Fama&ndash;MacBeth coefficient: regress the active contribution
w&middot;(r&#771; &minus; r&#771;&#7745;) on |w| within each month, average the monthly slopes, and take the
standard error from their month-to-month spread &mdash; the month-cluster SE a pooled regression
cannot give (it counts within-month correlated positions as independent and understates the SE ~40%).
The decay curve lines every position up by holding age and traces its directional idiosyncratic
return; the holding decomposition is the dollar-denominated companion. Every number is gated on the
independent-trade count, and below the gate the lab renders a refusal, not a point.</p>
{% endblock %}

{% block body_scripts %}
<script src="{{ asset_base | default('') }}assets/s3-lab.js"></script>
{% endblock %}
